There are 500K products and 2M audit logs. How do I make these efficient?

data.content:
Use **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** (EF Core 7+). These translate to single SQL statements — no entities loaded into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
var cutoffDate = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoffDate)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
        s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is fast:**
- **Before:** loads 500K/2M entities into memory, tracks them all, then sends individual UPDATE/DELETE statements
- **After:** generates a single `UPDATE ... SET IsActive = 0 WHERE LastSoldDate < @p0` and `DELETE FROM AuditLogs WHERE CreatedAt < @p0` — executed entirely server-side

**Key notes:**
- These bypass the change tracker entirely (no `SaveChangesAsync` needed)
- They ignore any unsaved in-memory changes to those entities
- If you have global query filters, they're applied automatically (use `IgnoreQueryFilters()` if you need to include filtered entities)
- For the 2M audit log delete, consider batching if your DB has lock escalation concerns:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
